# gen104 (L10): few-shot pattern induction in ONE turn — the signature emergent
# ability of LLMs (in-context learning), done deterministically. Given 2+
# labelled examples and a probe on a single line, parrot0 induces the rule the
# examples SHARE and applies it to a held-out item. The answer is NEVER stored:
# it is derived from the exemplars present in this very turn. Novel items each
# time, so no phrasebook can fake it (PRINCIPLES.md, anti-impostor).

# Suffix transform — append "s". parrot0 was never told the plural of "bird".
> cat -> cats, dog -> dogs, bird -> ?
< birds.
# The proof is real: it names the two examples and the rule it induced from them.
> how do you know?
< Because the examples cat -> cats and dog -> dogs share the rule "append 's'", so bird -> birds.

# Suffix transform with a longer affix — "+ing". Held-out verb.
> go -> going, see -> seeing, read -> ?
< reading.

# Suffix REPLACEMENT (not just append): drop the last char, append another.
> happy -> happier, lazy -> lazier, easy -> ?
< easier.

# Prefix transform — prepend "un". Symmetric to the suffix case.
> happy -> unhappy, kind -> unkind, fair -> ?
< unfair.

# Numeric: a constant delta induced from the examples (+2), applied to a probe.
> 1 -> 3, 4 -> 6, 10 -> ?
< 12.

# Numeric: an exact ratio (x3), held-out probe.
> 2 -> 6, 3 -> 9, 5 -> ?
< 15.

# SEMANTIC few-shot: the examples are not a string/number transform at all —
# they instantiate a RELATION. parrot0 was told three separate capital facts;
# from two example pairs it INFERS that the task is "capital of", then resolves
# the held-out probe from world knowledge. It deduced the task, not the answer.
> rome is the capital of italy
< Learned: capital(rome, italy).
> paris is the capital of france
< Learned: capital(paris, france).
> berlin is the capital of germany
< Learned: capital(berlin, germany).
> rome -> italy, paris -> france, berlin -> ?
< germany.
# The proof names the relation it inferred from the exemplars — derived, real.
> how do you know?
< Because the examples rome -> italy and paris -> france share the rule "capital(x, y)", so berlin -> germany.
# Same relation read BACKWARDS: the examples flip it, parrot0 follows. germany->berlin.
> italy -> rome, france -> paris, germany -> ?
< berlin.

# Honest miss: the shape is a few-shot frame, but no string, number, OR known
# relation fits. parrot0 says so rather than guessing a continuation.
> red -> blue, hot -> cold, up -> ?
< I see 2 examples, but I can't find one rule that fits them all.